Let F be closed in a compact space X, and let {U_i} be an open cover of F.
Since F is closed, X \ F is open, so {U_i} ∪ {X \ F} is an open cover of X; compactness of X gives a finite subcover U_{i_1}, …, U_{i_k}, X \ F.
Removing X \ F leaves U_{i_1}, …, U_{i_k}, which still cover F, so every open cover of F has a finite subcover and therefore F is compact.
